# Phase 3: Error Handling Refactor — Complete Design

## Preamble: What Memory Retrieved

Before writing a single line of design, I retrieved and cross-referenced:

| Source | Key Facts Extracted |
|---|---|
| **Active Constraints** | 4 constraints: 2 critical (RS256 JWT, Stripe webhook secret), 2 high (RFC 9457 format, Retry-After on 429) |
| **ADR-002** | Sliding window rate limiting; `X-RateLimit-Limit/Remaining/Reset` + `Retry-After` required on 429; fail-open on Redis failure |
| **ADR-003** | RFC 9457 Problem Details mandatory; `application/problem+json`; error type registry at `https://api.payments.example/errors/` |
| **API Spec** | RS256 JWT + API key auth; 401 vs 403 distinction required; rate limit tiers (Standard 100/min, Premium 500/min, Enterprise custom) |
| **Error Audit (Phase 2)** | 5 known issues: inconsistent formats, missing Retry-After on some 429s, stack traces in dev mode, trace_id missing on 5/8 endpoints, 401/403 conflated |
| **PCI-DSS Compliance** | Cardholder data must never appear in logs or error responses; all requests must be logged with timestamp/user/action/resource/result |
| **Security Findings** | SEC-2025-041 (RS256 mandatory, HS256 rejected — CRITICAL, active); SEC-2025-042 (refresh token replay — High, open) |

